      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>Hi, I'm AJ.</h1>
      <p>
        I'm Andreas Jackson, an analyst and builder in the San Francisco Bay
        Area. I
        studied business at UC Berkeley's Haas School (class of 2025, GPA 3.7,
        Dean's List), spent my student years running strategy engagements for
        clients like the Gates Foundation and IKEA, and now work in EY's
        financial services assurance practice.
      </p>
      <p>
        Outside the day job I like building things that have to survive
        contact with reality: <a href="/projects/nottomorrow">NotTomorrow</a>,
        a SaaS product with paying users, and
        <a href="/projects/dune-lakes-business">Dune Lakes</a>, a short-term
        rental business I help run. Both taught me more about pricing,
        customers, and margins than any coursework did.
      </p>
      <p>
        What ties it together: I like owning a number. Whether it's an audit
        workpaper, a partner-scoring model, or a night's ADR, I want to know
        how it was built and be able to defend it.
      </p>

      <h2>What I'm looking for</h2>
      <p>
        A full-time role where analytical rigor and shipping speed both
        matter: FP&amp;A or strategic finance, product management, data and
        analytics, or strategy and operations. Anywhere in the Bay Area works
        for me, San Francisco through the Peninsula and South Bay, and I'm
        also open to Santa Barbara or remote.
      </p>

      <h2>Off the clock</h2>
      <p>
        Chess, skiing, soccer, and following the semiconductor and data-center
        industry (yes, I've read Chip War). I also spend a lot of time
        experimenting with AI workflows, which you can read about in
        <a href="/how-i-work">how I work</a>.
      </p>

